## Frequently Asked Questions

### Are lab-grown diamonds real diamonds?
Yes. Lab-grown diamonds are physically, chemically, and optically identical to mined diamonds. The only difference is origin. The FTC recognizes them as real diamonds.

### Does Blue Nile sell both natural and lab-grown?
Yes. Blue Nile carries a full selection of both. Each listing clearly states whether it is natural or lab-grown, and the certification lab (GIA, IGI, or GCAL).

### Why are lab-grown diamonds at Blue Nile so much cheaper than natural?
The price reflects rarity, not quality. Natural diamonds took billions of years to form underground and millions of dollars to extract. Lab-grown diamonds are grown in weeks using controlled industrial processes. Same stone, different cost structure.

### Is IGI certification as good as GIA for lab-grown diamonds?
For lab-grown, both are widely accepted. GIA is the traditional standard for natural diamonds and carries more prestige. IGI has become the industry standard for lab-grown. At Blue Nile, IGI lab-grown diamonds are well-graded and legitimate. For 3ct+ purchases, GIA certification provides better resale documentation.

### Do lab-grown diamonds hold their value?
No, not significantly. Neither do natural diamond engagement rings in practice — most resell at 30–50% of retail. Lab-grown diamonds resell at even less due to continued price drops. If resale value matters, buy natural and think of it as a sentimental purchase, not an investment.

### What is GCAL certification?
GCAL (Gem Certification and Assurance Lab) is a respected third-party grading lab that certifies both natural and lab-grown diamonds. GCAL provides a light performance report alongside standard 4C grading. Their standards for lab-grown are on par with IGI and GIA. You'll see GCAL stones at Blue Nile, typically at a slight premium to IGI.

### Can you tell the difference between a lab-grown and natural diamond visually?
No. Not with the naked eye, not with a standard jeweler's loupe. Even a trained gemologist cannot distinguish them without specialized equipment that detects trace growth patterns. This is a physical reality, not a marketing claim.

